<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-568-368  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 568 368.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DBMS  June 1990 v3 n7 p36(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Database server performance. (includes related articles ontransactions and database manager performance parameters)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fosdick, Howard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Designers of database applications must always considerperformance.andP;  There are ways to maximize IBM's OS/2 EE DatabaseManager performance.andP;  To maximize efficiency in resolving a query,select only columns needed.andP;  Set up the query so that DatabaseManager uses a predefined index.andP;  There are two reasons to buildindexes: increase retrieval performance and to ensure theuniqueness of indexed columns.andP;  Joining tables increasesefficiency by supplying redundant information in the WHERE clausespecifying the join.andP;  Normalization, a technique or series ofsteps used in a number of database design methodologies, preventsanomalies during database maintenance, resulting in more stabledesigns.andP;  But normalization also results in designs with largenumbers of tables with few columns.andP;  De-normalization, combiningselected tables into a single table to alter a normalized databasedesign, should be used only when absolutely necessary.andP;  Aprogram's performance can be increased by using static SQL as muchas possible, minimizing the use of dynamic SQL, optimizingindividual queries within the program, ensuring that the overallSQL call pattern achieves the program's goals efficiently, andminimizing I/Os.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   OS/2 Extended Edition Database Manager (Data base managementsystem) (usage).andO;Topic:     Program Development TechniquesData Base ServersPerformanceStructured Query LanguageOS-2.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   When indexes are used. (table)When indexes are ignored. (table)When to create indexes. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>